Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of election fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments enacted new laws beginning in 2009 that made the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon gained momentum after the November 2010 elections, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in 2011 alone.
New election laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day and remove citizens with a judicial record from voting rights.
Prior to the 2006 election, no state in the United States required voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
In 2008, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a state government agency.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 did not have such an identity document.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required identity card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
Indeed, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
There's more.
Students, voters considered to vote more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their ID card with photo issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs that vote more on the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs to vote.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to make such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
It appears that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
In 2011, Republican lawmakers sponsored laws abolishing voter registration on polling day in eight states.
In addition, they have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to register about 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the registration rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have enacted laws in five other states aimed at shortening the pre-voting period.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of early voters were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state's voters.
It was the same with the Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites, who made up 76% of voters, accounted for only 46% of early voters.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of the Democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General stepped in to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have enacted laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID card.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undeniably make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that were passed and see it as an obvious goal to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that passed these laws account for 171 of the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have significant impacts on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
