The Higgs boson
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson created quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is indeed the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we are holding a genuine new particle, and that it looks very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, but data is still lacking to be perfectly certain.
Suppose it's Higgs anyway, since the chances of getting it wrong seem slim, and let's see what it is.
There is, in this world, a fatally inescapable law that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
Even though particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: the Pauli exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting roughly of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify the particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
And on the other side are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for this principle, which means they can actually be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not address here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature are propagated and to which the Higgs boson would be in some way related.
These bosons, it must be emphasized here, are not all animals as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this column, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" that is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle having an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field in this precise place, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" is born an electromagnetic wave (from light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and therefore, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, except that it is another field, the Higgs field, that needs to be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, one must reach very, very high energies, a bit like if it were a frozen pond of which only a very large rock could wrinkle the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN's - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27 km ring! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between Higgs and mass.
Not all particles and materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself on a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while others (like the photon, here) do not.
Now, what "can bring" all this research, asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancies between the observations and predictions of the MS.
There are also many who ardently wish that we find them, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physics" and plug some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has enormous deficiencies, offering no explanation for gravity (ops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter in the Universe (re-ops!).
But no such discrepancies have been found at CERN so far.
Consequences
The repercussions of this research in the daily life of Monsieur et Madame Tout-le-Monde are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
In the early 1960s, the laser pioneers at Bell Laboratories had no idea of the revolution their work was about to trigger.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed), in 1962 - once told us - at first the laser was rather seen as a "lab gadget".
Imagine...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, although not at all its original intention, now serves as an "eye" to all the digital cameras in the world, and earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This of course does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, we never know...
Palliative care - The best way to die... <0x7C> The Duty
With its Dying with Dignity Commission, Quebec has recently debated the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate is expected to resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this essential area.
Duty has tried to look at it more closely.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was eating him up had left him with a two-year respite.
"They had given me five years to live, I was seven," he said, half-fig half-grape, lying in his bed at the palliative care home Victor-Gadbois, of Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he said.
The disease does its job: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the toilet alone, and even from eating alone.
Sitting in front of an appetizing lunch, he agrees to let himself help eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even manages to smile, talks to strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicines, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My biggest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it's humiliating," he said.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man, it pisses standing," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois house.
Returning to the child’s stage, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability" to accept the regression, he notes.
For, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great moments take place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide so-called "curative" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is of dying “consciously and suffocated.”
But the disease made me discover my children.
“I have good kids,” she added.
“I don’t have any wishes in life anymore,” she said, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
She is still waiting, in the next few days, for a final visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, with a group of volunteers, body care and food assistance are provided.
These are palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed per 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little when you know that we all end up dying one day.
Here, life goes on in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at the house.
Whether at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When dying, we will agree to provide oral care to brandy or Pepsi, depending on the request.
Diabetics will no longer have to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night, Mr. X, who died overnight, was served a beer.
This morning, it is his son who will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help loved ones as much as patients," says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow but are not the same.
Alongside a 93-year-old man savoring his last family gathering in the yard, stuck in his pillows while drinking in his honor, a 36-year-old boy tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, after trying everything to survive.
"For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," Dr. Christiane Martel said.
53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home arrive from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
The Problem of Access to Palliative Care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, which is care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal stage of his or her life, whether at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Greater Montreal Palliative Home Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec's health care that causes several doctors specializing in palliative care to fear the adoption of a law governing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care leaders including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to testify their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not performing well enough to ensure that everyone will be entitled to quality palliative care before they agree to euthanasia.
Recently, she said, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room, in great pain, without being relieved.
I fear that patients will only ask to die because they are not receiving adequate care.
And at the same time, several oncologists are hard on their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognoses.
Helene Richard's survival expectations were already minimal when she gave up trying chemotherapy.
When I announced to my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she replied that she regretted that I was stopping fighting, she said.
Yet she told me I was finished!
No Almighty Care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for not complying with their request after they have been relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Société de soins palliatifs à domicile du Grand Montréal, patients would be refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which means that the patient falls asleep until the moment of death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of the suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved always say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But it doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” it means “I want to be relieved.”
