A constitution with forceps in Egypt
This is a new poker move from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, it has decided to play its part.
Taking everyone on board, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state gave this Assembly two more months to complete its work.
For almost two years Egypt has been relying on a provisional text, several times amended, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative has only increased the divide in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his "autocratic delusion", continuing to "betray his word" and "treat the law".
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time that obliges the Brothers to give up their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy as protest rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour, as he claimed in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since this use of a hasty vote is an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I keep the full powers", these supposedly to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large Islamist majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals were missing the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they slammed the door, believing they had not been able to assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, replacement members, were added in haste, yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, most of the articles were voted on unanimously.
Commentators were amused by the fact that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around... the time of prayer, some members of the committee felt that the pendulum of the constituent was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, has 234 articles.
Objects of all attention, article 2 ultimately remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to be able to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed a stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," respond the Liberals, who see it only as a blow to communication.
Because according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They include Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the conformity of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see in it the beginnings of a theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are further fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil status.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system," said Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on Egypt's constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around article 220, because the terms used borrow from the religious vocabulary.
This refers to "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence].
And the question may arise in the future as to the extent to which civilian judges are competent to rule on it."
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extended powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the former regime.
Another controversial point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will trials of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as demanded by human rights associations.
They also express their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and the insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences on freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, there are no more articles echoing the protection of women, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In her view, the only positive point was the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, protests are scheduled this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will parade on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the Center of the World and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the grandeur of biblical truths, modern comfort, and wilderness.
Argumenty i Fakty has selected five main reasons to visit Israel.
Go and love the holy places
A must-see: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who enters these “baptismal funds” will be touched by divine grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm or where the fishing was miraculous.
This is where Jesus appeared to his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places is in Jerusalem.
The believers walk the Rue de la Souffrance or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the fortress Antonia (the praetorium), where the trial was held, and then leads through the streets of the old city to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the Anointing and of the burial.
Here is the Christian centre of the world, symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where grew the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest place of the Jews: the Wailing Wall which constitutes the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different denominations leave small words accompanied by prayers that are then answered.
Travel in height
Visit the ruins of the Masada Fortress, an ancient refuge from enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can get there on their own.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont which welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
The old beliefs are that pagan gods once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth a visit.
First of all: the Israel Museum located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the very ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
See also: Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
It mainly exhibits the paintings of the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of moulds of visitors and supervisors of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the unique private Ralli Museum where you can admire sculptures by Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Entrance is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the children's memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and enter into total darkness.
Stars are shining.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
Israel’s three major seaside resorts lie on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, because the water temperature does not drop below 21° while that of the air can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, 417 m below sea level.
The azure-colored water contains brine and very easily retains swimmers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of surreal beauty.
We come to perform a treatment based on salt water, silt, curative sludge and to treat different diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of antiquity
They are guarded by the old city of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shore of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris that connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it is here that Noah built his ark and that Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists especially like to stroll through the narrow alleys that bear the name of the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you will be able to meet newlyweds who came to take photoshoots from all over Israel and even from other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater, "conquer" the Crusader fortress.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, notably Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to the euro, as they are easily exchangeable into shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
As far as urban transport is concerned, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and capable of connecting the lower and upper parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
The journey in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition is to celebrate the Sabbath on the Sabbath.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturdays, markets, shops and public transport cease to operate.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, scaleless fish, and dishes consisting of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of dishes based on lamb and beef, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish dough, different sauces, ground chickpea balls, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, we find many well-fed cats who walk around in the haughty air.
We can see them at night sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
These cats love passing places and do not refuse to be fed.
Renting a car varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24h (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Admission to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
Three million tourists from around the world visited Israel in 2012.
These were mainly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before visa cancellation on February 9, 2011.
"Who has language, to Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
As deputies and human rights activists argue over what the mandatory language test law will give, fraudsters selling "fake" certificates have already appeared in the country
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are Central Asian nationals: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to earn money to help their families stay at home.
As of December 1, a law has come into force and stipulates that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian exam.
For the time being, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also that of the history of Russia and the foundations of law.
It will be necessary to validate his/her language knowledge in Russian to obtain and renew his/her work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has the status of official language are exempt.
Persons who obtained certificates or educational diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Profit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centers will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, People's Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the exams in all the cities of the country: more than 160 centers have already been opened throughout the territory.
This initiative to introduce reviews was supported by members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders have repeatedly asked the question in the press: what will it mean?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, respond the representatives of the migration service, this will reduce the number of people suffering "from slavery at work".
Many talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, explains Victor Sebelev, director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for migrants without profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "journey" to an overcrowded house where he and dozens of his peers will torment themselves for months without food and without paper and will have to work between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"They are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are cheated, their passports are taken, and they do not receive the salary," said Tolib Charipov, head of the Migration Services Directorate for Labour of Tajikistan's Migration Service.
Don't argue with me, policeman!
However, many nationals of Central Asian republics who wish to come to make money in Russia say that they not only do not know the language of the country where they wish to go, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is of course not their fault, but their misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to attend even a passable primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children, not to mention dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people leave to make money as soon as the opportunity presents itself.
It's hard when you don't know the language, they say.
"You feel diminished and diminished."
Human rights defenders, however, note an important aspect of the language law.
The examinations will only be for migrants who have legal status.
Without statute, there will be no formal examination or work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or defend to enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and still these linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 miles rubles.
And then you can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have fake documents, that we do not have a record, hence the cases of extortion.
"They are asking us for 100, 200 rubles, something to buy cigarettes, tea," Umed Khushkadamov, a Tajik national, told reporters.
“Hurry up, don’t skimp and buy yourself a beautiful work of art.”
From the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was discovered that migrant registration papers were not the only ones to be false.
Several false language exam certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
Falsified papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not get them for nothing: each migrant who hoped to facilitate the task of exams had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
It is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Officials and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these “paper scraps”.
The authorities can give migrant workers who have not been able to pass the first-time exam time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against the bearers of civilian weapons.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether it was the shooting at weddings or the killing organized by the Moscow jurist Dmitry Vinogradov, which left seven dead.
The police want to ban the wearing of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a gun licence from 18 to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma’s committee for security and anti-corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the arms law would be introduced in the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is satisfied to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "tightening the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demand to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC, told the Russian service.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, over a six-month period in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that strengthening civil arms laws will not prevent criminals from sourcing from the black market.
According to them, any weapon can be found in Moscow today for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior says it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: From the factory to the officer
The arms black market is supplied through several channels.
There are five main channels, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served ten years in the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot taken from a site taking weapons orders
The first is "the military trace", that is, the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians," Baranets said.
The second type of black market weapons are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stockpiles and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal guns go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of them have often suffered explosions.
"Attested versions indicate that some fires were deliberately set in order to conceal the deficit," the former soldier said.
For Baranets, the weapons manufacturers are for something.
“We see private weapons factories that do not compete with the competition in the international market and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow,” says an expert.
One of the other sources of the black market is smuggling.
A significant proportion of pistols and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply," adds the former military.
Where do the guns come from?
Experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on the issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Specialists analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the military and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market ended up there “because of employees whose work is linked to weapons,” the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from military conflict sites, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% are from “illegal excavations”.
A salesman and consultant at an armory who asked to remain anonymous said that no one has bought the weapons found by these underground excavators for a long time; they are too old.
Most often, according to him, sellers will pick up the new goods from military warehouses.
The person buys a unit, for example a TT gun, through a sign.
We deliver it to him by passing the merchandise through a wire mesh.
"He transports it to the city and resells it for <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>900 per unit with two chargers," he says.
"It is true that the police are aware of all the cases, so when crimes are about to be solved, they make a control purchase from illegal arms dealers," the seller added.
"Like in a luxury boutique"
The seller and the buyer are usually found through knowledge.
I consulted websites, blogs, until a guy showed up and asked me to come to the Begovaya station where someone was going to take me to a "corner" to bargain.
The price of the gun, they gave it to me on the spot
Victor Baranets as a military observer
To find a gun, I have to know someone who has a contact, the salesman explains. I know someone, but I don't trust them.
There are sellers in the markets, but there you also have to come by saying for example "On behalf of such a person, who asked me to convey that his daughter has lost a tooth".
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of a person I trust.
He only gives them to me because he knows I won't give them to him.
The new little ones are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former militaryman Victor Baranets tried himself as a buyer of illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
The patterns, according to him, have not changed.
We gave him a photo album in which there was "everything we want".
"I thought I was in a luxury shop," recalls the soldier.
There is no secret for the buyer, Baranets explains, we can try anything.
As a potential customer, I don't just buy, we go with the seller to the forest and install a target.
“I’m allowed to fire and when I’m convinced that the weapon is working well, we start negotiating,” he said.
A shop from the sofa
Search engines display sites and groups on Vkontakte where you can buy weapons "for different uses".
For this, we do not need any documents and no one to meet.
"It is enough to have a precise sum of money," the ad reads on the site "Buy a pistol or a combat machine gun."
Users leave their request and ask their questions.
