Childbirth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Global warming or collision with a deadly asteroid.
Space shuttle caravans with Earthlings on board set off in search of a rescue planet.
To save humanity, a big question arises: how can we continue to keep our species alive in weightlessness or on a rescue planet?
I don't think there's much choice.
There are actually two real planets that can be conquered, if only by hypothesis.
"It's about Venus and Mars," said Vladimir Sourdine, a researcher at the P.K. Chternberg State Astronomical Institute (GAICh).
If on Mars the conditions are more suitable for life, the temperature on the surface of Venus is 500 .
We can only live there at very high altitudes or on the orbit of Venus... in space.
We began to focus on the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on flora.
Half a century ago, experiments were carried out on plants.
Four generations of small peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from terrestrial varieties.
Then we put into orbit insects, small reproductive drosophilous flies.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to see how a weightless embryo developed.
We get at the exit a quite normal chick.
It is then that the problems begin.
"The problem is related to the fact that the chick has to find support, it has to get on its legs and start moving," explains the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP) Vladimir Sychev.
When they found no support, the chicks shook in a disorderly manner.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophy.
The chicks did not react to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
“We opened their eyes twice, and then we gave up, because it is simply impossible to work with them there,” says Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with chicks in space.
The last biological "miniature ark" with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, the biosatellite " Bion " will only embark on species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetus into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural has been discovered.
"It was still about biosatellites and then it's the only experiment. We have to do this kind of research," remarks Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, space rats gave birth to their offspring.
However, it is not yet possible to make reproductions directly in space.
It's not a small business.
By losing their usual environment, animals are no longer able to realize their sexual instincts.
Unlike animals, humans are capable of this in principle.
Homo sapiens possesses abstract thinking, it is able to create a suitable emotional background.
This type of experiment is not carried out for ethical reasons.
But women have been in space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was taken by Terechkova.
And the female organism is what humanity has most precious.
Our seagull flew away and no one on Earth could tell if it would hold up after a flight into space.
If she could have given birth to a child after the theft.
“Nobody was answering that question,” said Vakhtang Vachnadze, a retired rocket and space executive.
In June 1964, just one year after her flight into space, the first female cosmonaut Valentina Terechkova gave birth to a little girl.
The father of the child, Andrian Nikolayev was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second female cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, after having been twice in orbit and even working in an extra-vehicular environment, gave birth to a son.
However, the risk persists.
We have few, even very few cosmonauts who have had nothing and who give birth to a healthy offspring after long flights.
"And if they are longer, it presents a danger even during flights in orbit," concludes the pilot and cosmonaut, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of Russia, Valeriy Poliakov.
Yet humanity must seek new solutions in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravitation.
Hydrology laboratory of the Cosmonaut Preparation Center: mandatory stage of flight preparation.
Here, in zero buoyancy, cosmonauts train at extra-vehicle exits.
Water imitates weightlessness.
If for adults, water is comfortable but nevertheless a foreign environment, for infants, it is their true element.
Small amphibious men seem to confirm this: life on Earth comes from the ocean.
Since the baby is about 9 months in the lymphatic fluid of the mother's belly, it is easier to get used to the water afterwards.
This is in principle logical, because from birth until his first bath, it takes only 2 weeks.
“It’s very little to forget,” explains infant swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
In a word, if for the newborn child weightlessness is a more natural state, the woman needs gravitation, a force of weight.
In weightlessness, the muscles of the belly, the pelvis atrophy very quickly, the baby's thrust capacity is lost.
All right, let's ignore that by relying on the birth simulators.
Of course, you can prepare a childbirth in a special room, the woman will manage to get it out.
"And then?" asks Valeriy Poliakov to invite to reflect on this complex question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravitation.
If it does not feel the terrestrial attraction, the body does not form the skeleton or the muscular system.
One cannot dress an infant as an adult with a special suit for training.
He will simply be deprived of his vital needs.
"And this experience that we would consider in this case imagining the birth of a child in a foreign environment will result in the return to Earth of a disabled child, completely inadapted," predicts the Director of the Committee for Bioethics of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences, Igor Pestov.
The birth of children in space is still a matter of theory.
However, over time this will become a reality, when the Earthlings will travel in their shuttles to a distant planet that will become the habitat of their spaceborn offspring.
