Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member state of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started working closely with ESA in 1994 and in the following years participated in a number of ESA projects.
The journey from Poland to space, however, began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the lecture of A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on December 6, 1933, in which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the auditors cold and years later <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch awards in France for his book Introduction to Astronautics.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a propagator of world-renowned astronautics, his contribution was notably rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters of the hidden face of the Moon.
In 1925 a draisine was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket would be used to propel or brake the draisin.
The only known information about this draisine is from the press of the time.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was carried out by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It is clear from the preserved documents that this research had reached the test stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937, plans of a photoelectric hunting rocket, drawn by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other work devoted to aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is talk of a company in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Problème, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (established in 1951) and as early as the autumn, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, the RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
An upgraded version, the RM-1A, was later built, and during the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket began in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was halted.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded the first rockets of type RM.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B it was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C it was 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the Aeronautics Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Thereafter, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Poland joined COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and a national COSPAR committee was established two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the law on public works.
This decision has raised a lively debate in public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means that the different economic entities as well as the national economic systems are perpetually in conflict with each other.
This results from the principle of free trade and the free (unlimited) movement of private capital combined with unbridled financial speculation.
The considerable differences in the price of labour (wages) generate a tension on prices.
This is to be understood as meaning that a producer endeavours, by importing goods sold cheaply, to withstand economic competition by "making the price of the competitor more expensive" in order to take away a larger share of the market and thereby increase his own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transfer production abroad, or buy cheaply, or disappear. The result is high unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it engenders, the social charges of the State necessarily increase.
All this situation intensifies the perfect unwillingness of gentlemen entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to society as a whole by this race for profit.
This situation is so well known that there is no need to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create in the different economies a situation in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to them.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without regard for social collapse.
This is mainly manifested in the amendments to the laws in force.
The objective is to economically force its own population to accept the diktat of private capital prices, especially in the field of wages.
This is achieved, on the one hand, by a system of economic constraints in case of long-term unemployment and, on the other hand, by the restriction of the rights of employees in the field of labour legislation.
The result is growing poverty and deepening differences between the rich and the poor.
In the FRG, for years there have been public distribution points of food for the poor who cannot support themselves with their own work.
There are already millions of these people.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it becomes quite common for employees to receive such wages that the state is forced to pay an extra to ensure that they reach the minimum living wage.
Such a scandal has for example been brought to light in the case of employees working as auxiliaries in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of practically all the southern EU Member States generate, without a doubt, a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the nineteenth century) or to live with wages of misery, on the margins of society, in the hope that their capital will be invested in the day.
The question must be asked here: where does this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will pass from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or else a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media are tired of saying that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the led economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
It is then necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence, and even direct today, according to its own selfish interests, politics and thereby the whole state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof of this is that there is an almost all-powerful lobby in every state.
The result is a desperate situation manifesting itself in the field of corruption, through the granting of mutual advantages, in the legislation, where everything is condemnable but not punishable.
In the FRG, the situation is such that due to a lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the drafting of legislation to law firms closely linked to the industry.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
All power does not come from the people, as the Western-type constitutions state, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is evident that liberal-oriented democracies are now rapidly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Time of Caesar and Pompey": "The state had long been in full decay and functions were assigned by violence.
Bribes, favors obtained illegally, and stones and swords were also used to obtain these positions.
The absolute underpants and corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with votes already sold"...... "Honest people did not seek to obtain any functions, it resulted once the state remained 8 months without consuls".... 'It was really started to say that the remedy to this difficult situation was a 'spirit', which was transformed into an 'autocracy' and that it was necessary to choose a man"
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the present society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard for the interest of society as a whole.
In its essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and assert the interests of society as a whole.
The result, today as in the past, is a decadence without precedent of elites, without any effort to carry out profound reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems in favour of liberal-type democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites are completely unaware of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the humanitarian and social crises we are witnessing today as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both internationally and internally in Europe, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways of decreasing the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution lies in socio-political reforms, which will strengthen state capital investment in the economy, increase citizens' influence over the government, and weaken the position of monopoly of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
