The architects of the firm MVRDV prove that true adventures are not only a matter of imagination. To be convinced, it is enough to contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
“I think this building is funny, it looks very futuristic, finally something interesting to see,” Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the street side, tells us.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large neighboring company, tells us: "Yes, it is indeed beautiful, this building".
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Nowadays, nobody goes to one of those nasty libraries voluntarily, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeping town that has nothing attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to give back some neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictional bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of pretty little miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to get their hands on the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, from the Rotterdam MVRDV architects' office, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of spirited and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and entered the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a laugh on his face.
And while the jury members were still staring at each other, bewildered and shrugging, Maas, the bold one, stacked his books of choice in order of size to make a pyramid, and ended his speech supported by activist arguments with a: "Common dear!"
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain spilled out of the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and semi-detached houses for a total of 50 homes.
At the beginning of November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this dull little town, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a town hall of astonishing ugliness, whose white facades invite you to think that they house a dairy, has been enriched with a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under the cheese bell.
Certainly, an elevator transports you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you step on the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the floor made of Dutch bricks and elegant street lights speak unequivocally the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public benches, dogs and little boys and girls who play ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally, the library shelves are located along the facade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,” explains Willy Maas.
We have completely upended the classical spatial configuration and opened up the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been cleverly arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A special beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes panelling, sometimes balustrades, sometimes stair ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened architects and building engineers do not want unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
Thus, one day we found in a Frisian agricultural enterprise an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, one-millimeter-thick synthetic membrane has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and it saves time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and transforms into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and potted ficus.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal humidity level of the literary mountain air.
Gifts for the New Soul
“It’s incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books lies beneath a glass bell, the sun illuminates the interior only for a short time, even on good weather days.
The thick wooden beams mounted sideways with respect to the glass facade serve as a sun visor, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The ambiance is very pleasant.
The fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "soul finally found".
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure has helped fill the gaps in the library that was not yet fully filled (today, it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays overflow from all sides.
For architect Winy Maas, “there is nothing worse than a half-empty library.”
"I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it’s just for decoration.”
This is how MVRDV has achieved the master discipline called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
Although it may seem young and poorly educated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinians' request for observer status at the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
Why? Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but without being too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 insurgency in Libya, Germany also chose to abstain in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Eventually, NATO imposed this measure.
Is Germany struggling to take a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy as it were defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans are fighting on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe they are still groping to find this role, but are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Britain
What, then, does the term "normal" foreign policy actually mean for the Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national dossiers.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, that is, by its exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
The economic interests of Germany are, to a certain extent, different from those of the other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany’s stance on the Middle East conflict and abstention in the UN vote?
Germany first has important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to clash with public opinion, but also with the elites of the Arab countries.
There is no doubt that this is a decisive factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, because it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is, in any case, a decisive element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany harm its relations with the United States by choosing to abstain in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think the Europeans and the Americans understand the German position perfectly.
That is why I think the fracture is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Indeed, Germany has thus shown that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, the views on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
The United States, on the other hand, announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do the opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot of course defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overflowing with enthusiasm for Netanyahu’s policy.
Is Germany struggling to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think it makes things easier for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They cannot therefore be part of a broader political line and must affirm their singular position.
This is what they are currently doing on the issue of the euro.
In my opinion, Germany will take on a locomotive role in the future and push Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, especially because of its relations with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive issue.
