"Brand Protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but that has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the company bearing its name cannot lodge a complaint.
And even if she could, he's not sure she'd win the case.
“It’s becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing’s Far East property law firm.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Imitators only need a few extra letters to be able to register their trademarks.
So instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sports goods.
Pattloch opens a folder in which registrations made with the Beijing Trademark Office can be found.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the brand Zegna DF Puma, a name that the firm artificially created by appropriating part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a well-known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions of copying and infringing intellectual property.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell virtually only counterfeits.
Pattloch's cases, however, are different: its constituents charge him with addressing the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese speak of "Bang Mingpai", a related brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is by this term that women who marry rich men are referred to.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to complain about.
“It’s bad for business, we have to fight this trend,” Pattloch said.
"The brand is sweetened, the uniqueness disappears, the damage to reputation is enormous."
Financial losses and legal costs are in the millions for the sectors concerned, especially for expensive flagships.
According to data from market analysis firm CLSA, China represents, with an annual volume of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>15 billion, the world's third-largest and fastest-growing market for luxury goods.
However, it is not easy to delete dubious registrations from the trademark registry and these procedures are expensive.
They can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch cites trials in which the court dismissed the complaint, because after a long time, the criticized name had become a "market reality".
Pattloch explains that if the complainant is unlucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist, as he would have harmed his brand in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against construction machine manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just bought concrete pump producer Putzmeister.
This is why the Chinese can use an emblem that resembles the Mercedes star.
Geely, Volvo's acquirer, used a blue and white logo reminiscent of BMW's. The conflict was settled and Geely had to change it.
The fashion house Lacoste had lost against the plagiarists of Hong Kong and Singapore who had redirected the look of the famous crocodile in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
The CTMO Trademark Office in Beijing admits, however, that it experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, the Office reportedly went last year from a "situation of emergency in the course of work to a normality found".
Thus, the number of unprocessed opposition procedures would have decreased by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 such cases were reportedly closed, representing a 75% increase over the previous year.
Nonetheless, 81,500 proceedings remain pending at the Office.
Acting is expensive
As is often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the Office, this is a record and means that China is at the top of the ranking for the number of new deposits in the world for the tenth time in a row.
This would also apply to the total number of legal trademarks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the Office reportedly recorded 1.8 billion yuan of registration fees.
In other words, each record earned an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as illustrated by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the company has been battling a Chinese plagiarist.
Certainly, the Germans were able to get the illegal manufacture of vehicle components to be suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain its Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
“It’s our fault, because surnames can’t be protected in Germany,” says Hanno Wentzler, chairman of the board of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The Trademark Office therefore rejected the objection of the Munichians.
Freudenberg certainly won in the next two instances, but the opposing side continues to fight to this day.
Vigilance is required
The case is currently pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, he believes in a positive outcome of the trial and boasts the professionalism of the judges.
Nevertheless, he adds: "the procedure is long, strenuous and costs us a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to assess internal costs, and the Archives department has even had to review the records of the past hundred years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg even offered the opposing party a "large six-digit euro sum" to settle the dispute.
“That’s what we see what it means to us,” Wentzler says.
The dangers of the Far East even threaten to overflow to Europe.
This would be the case if imitators from this region ensured the exploitation of unprotected trademarks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to register in Germany the name Freudenberg for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long since abandoned this sector, but it could still have prevented the deposit.
Wentzler adds: "Watchfulness is required."
Pattloch and him advised German companies to exercise great caution in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, according to them, to rely on international trademark law, foreigners should rather "register also in China everything that is likely to be protected", as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, the costs may be much higher than those of registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the last act of his legal drama, the company would have to pay licensing fees to the opposing party for the use of its own name, as Wentzler explains.
Otherwise, we would lose our place in the market segment in question.
