Imbongi means "storyteller" or "singer of praise" in Zulu.
No one can fluently speak the Bantu language in this area, but everyone can sing it.
For almost 10 years, the choir has been rehearsing songs in this foreign language that it has brought to Germany to now return it to its native region: South Africa.
At 8,733 kilometres as the crow flies from Heidelberg, in the northwest of the Kingdom of Swaziland, is Esitjeni, the village that depends on the vocal power of the German choir.
40% of people affected
The village has about 2,000 inhabitants, some living in modest straw or dirt huts and the majority of them are children.
More than 300 of them are orphans because HIV has taken away their parents.
In Esitjeni, we can observe on a smaller scale the ills that plague Swaziland: the highest rate of HIV infection and the lowest life expectancy in the world according to UNICEF.
The population hardly ever accepts male circumcision, a measure that nevertheless guarantees a proven reduction in the risk of infection by half.
More than 40% of the population of Swaziland is carrier of the immunodeficiency virus and it is not uncommon to die in their mid-thirties.
During a group trip to Africa in the spring of 2005, the choir had been able to discover the village. The Imbongis especially saw many children on the street who lacked not only parental care, but also simply everything: food, clothing, education.
In a poor country without a school diploma, there is simply no prospect.
In the beginning, it was just a few people who personally committed to paying a few euros each year so that they could send a child to school and offer him a hot meal a day.
But barely a year later, the choir founded Voices for Africa, an association that has since dealt almost professionally with AIDS orphans in Esitjeni.
Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
Common STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
Pubic lice and scabies belong to the parasitic STIs.
Which groups are mainly concerned?
Syphilis and gonorrhea often occur in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute estimates that sexual contact between men is responsible for at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia-related infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungal), gonorrhea and human papillomavirus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of HIV spread among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany, however, some 20% of new HIV infections are observed within this group.
In young people, the rate of chlamydia-related infections is significantly higher than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections are among young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In addition, in Germany, human papillomavirus is common among young people.
What is the evolution of the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert-Koch Institute, the number of syphilis cases has more than doubled in 10 years: the figure has increased from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has been decreasing.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one tenth compared to the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual illness?
Infectious diseases can cause abscesses in the genitals, urinary pain, white discharge, lower abdomen pain and the appearance of pimples and warts.
However, they do not regularly cause any pain or other symptoms and therefore remain hidden.
How to protect yourself?
Condoms can decrease the risk of infection, but they do not protect 100%.
The reason for this is that sexually transmitted disease pathogens can also be transmitted through lubricating infection or through close body contact.
Experts therefore recommend that anyone who frequently changes sexual partners take regular examinations.
Most early-stage STIs can be cured and late-stage sequelae can be prevented.
