After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were detained by the military.
The state must also protect "the true nature of the Egyptian family" and "promote its morals and values".
From a legal point of view, the wording is so vague that state institutions could even control the content of cinematography and literature.
In other words, it would simply be censorship.
Furthermore, no article expressly guarantees equality between men and women.
Instead, another article forbids offending or defaming the Prophet Muhammad or his envoys.
However, the article does not define what an offence is or how it should be punished.
Equally dubious is the wording implying that it is forbidden to "offend people".
Is it enough to draw a cartoon of the president or to tell a joke at the expense of a lawyer?
Many points are therefore subject to interpretation in the draft that Morsi puts to the vote and which, in his own words, will "very soon" be the subject of a referendum with the Egyptians.
"The revolution was reborn"
The opposition has been mobilizing for weeks against the numerical superiority of Islamists.
On Friday night, tens of thousands of protesters gathered in unusual harmony in Cairo’s Tahrir Square, promising to bring down sharia law before it takes effect.
"The revolution is reborn and we are going to win," said Hamdin Sabbahi, third in the presidential election.
Nobel Peace Prize laureate and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency Mohamed El Baradei said the draft constitution is "to be thrown into the trash can of history."
On Twitter, the instant messaging service, he accused Morsi's supporters of wanting to foment a "putsch against democracy".
