For its part, the well-organized Muslim Brotherhood called for a counter-demonstration not on Tahrir Square as a precautionary measure, but on the other side of the Nile, where a great prayer was organized in front of the University of Cairo.
The veiled women and supporters of the Salafists, who participated in large numbers, chanted: "the people demand the application of the law of God."
"Clean up our country!" they asked Morsi, saying that "the Koran [was their] Constitution."
A struggle for sovereignty on the symbolic Tharir Square, where it all began, would soon have created a situation similar to that of a civil war.
Obviously, that’s what Morsi’s supporters wanted to avoid.
The Muslim Brotherhood said that opponents of the draft Constitution, as well as its supporters, had spoken out loud.
According to them, it is now time to let the people decide at the polls what direction the country should take.
The project of the Islamists will certainly win the majority.
“Human rights are not mentioned once.”
Hafez Abu Saeda is angry at this imposed constitutional process that should have lasted until February and encompassed all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and president of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EOHR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood while they were in prison or in court under Mubarak.
He did so not because he shared their conception of the world, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
That's why he was beaten, tried and imprisoned.
"And now, the term is not even pronounced once in the new Constitution," he regretted during his interview with the Welt am Sonntag.
The extension of Morsi’s powers to the three powers discouraged the lawyer.
These measures are blatant violations of the rules of democracy and will create a new dictatorship in Egypt.
“Instead of strengthening civil society, the president de facto strips it of all its powers,” Saeda said.
Yet a democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels neglected, including by the international community, which watches the battle between the different political ideologies on the Nile bank with a mixture of curiosity and nervousness.
That could pay off.
A protester in Tharir Square warns: "You are giving birth to a monster that you will no longer be able to control."
Norway's rakfisk: is it the most fragrant fish in the world?
The five million people living in Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but also in the world.
Could the secret of the country's success be related to the locals' appetite for extremely smelly fish?
Take some advanced cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of wet and dirty football clothes.
Wait a week.
And you get the disturbing smell of rakfisk, one of Norway’s most prized dishes.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about 3 hours from Oslo.
It snows, the landscape is spectacular - and this ubiquitous smell permeates the air.
The rakfisk consists of salt sprinkled trout and fermented in water for a duration - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can go up to a year.
When the darkness sets in and it is cold, Norwegians gather en masse to attend a festival here in Fagernes dedicated to this incredible culinary specialty.
“You eat raw, then you swallow a glass of aquavit,” says Havard Halvarsen, a full-time local firefighter also known as “Rakfisk General,” who is in charge of running the festival.
Around us, people swallow small pieces of fish and put on a large amount of drink.
“Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk,” adds Havard.
The drink kills the smell.
I'll try a few pieces.
If you can avoid getting it under your nose, it’s not bad – it sounds like a sushi that would have spent long hours on a bus.
The rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before the invention of refrigeration, the fish was immersed in barrels of airtight water, then salted in autumn.
Then, during the winter, once well fermented, the fish came out and - no doubt with the senses diminished by alcohol - ate.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country to find work, mostly emigrating to the United States.
Now, the population is growing rapidly – more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by full employment, high wages and a comprehensive health system.
The Swedes, their old rivals whose country was not so long richer than Norway, cross the border to come to work.
The rakfisk is considered to be something important, a vital, though odorous, element of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive dishes.
But everything is expensive - a small pint of beer or a sandwich will cost you 10 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> each.
Norway is not often mentioned in international news, which is not to its displeasure.
Here, people are unwilling to talk about Anders Breivik, the right-wing racist extremist who shot 77 people, including women and children.
When they talk about this killing, they talk about the “July 22 incident.”
The Norwegians are struggling to accept that in their peaceful country, one of their own might have committed such an act of barbarism.
Since the early 1970s, Norway owes its wealth to its oil and gas industry, one of the largest in the world.
“But oil is not the only reason that justifies our success,” explains Anna, our waitress, with blond hair and pierced blue eyes, the image of Nordic well-being, with a rakfisk tray in her hand.
We are, as you say, cautious people.
His English, like most people who live here, is perfect.
We are discreet, we do not like to be noticed.
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution - everything except a small percentage of money from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When other countries were throwing money out of the windows, in the years that led us to the international financial crisis, Norway was able to keep the strings of its purse tight.
"As long as you can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"Without forgetting the rakfisk," she adds in a carefree laugh.
I stand in the snow and queue to buy myself something to eat - I got my dose of rakfisk.
On the menu, a burger made of impulse, a real discovery, is excellent.
But tonight, the smell of fish is everywhere.
The hotel I'm staying in is one of the many places where rakfisk is served for dinner and where one can vote for the best of them - or perhaps for the most odorous of them.
There is a TV show where the presenter carries a butterfly knot, surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It was like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score did you give to the best fish in the Thor-Juergen Mountains?"
"Here are our points, Havard."
We hear laughter and applause.
A man falls from his chair, perhaps because of the abuse of aquavit.
Or maybe it's because of the fish fumes.
Mexican Enrique Pena Nieto has a tough start.
As incoming President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office in Mexico, Will Grant of the BBC is interested in the difficulties that await him and the expectations of the people, which are many.
Traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad at the moment.
In a city where traffic is legion in normal times, a security dam has been put in place since Monday, blocking several key road accesses in the capital and causing real chaos on the roads.
Nevertheless, the aim was not to prevent people from going to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching Parliament.
Next Saturday, the new president of Mexico, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential scarf to become the new president at the head of the nation.
A complicated task awaits him.
Mexico’s economy is doing well, with results owed to outgoing President Felipe Calderon, but the country is plagued by a drug war that has already claimed the lives of about 60,000 people in six years.
“My government has made a commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence,” Mr. Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Before joining the US president, Mr. Pena Nieto was governor of the state of Mexico.
A very populated and sprawling state that encircles the capital. On his favorite land, opinions about this new leader are divided.
A direct man
In the bucolic municipality of Valle del Bravo, for example, it is inscribed in the memory of all.
The locals attribute to it the development of tourism and infrastructure in the municipality.
To reach the city, you can take one of the new motorways of M Pena Nieto, a major improvement has been made to these roads, once bumpy and full of crevices.
Plaques bearing his name are hung on the outside of a new sports complex and an impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
"We are counting on him to put in place lasting changes," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a member of Congress and of Mr Pena Nieto's party, the PRI.
In terms of security and economics in particular, we hope for a real change that our country needs so much.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace in Los Pinos, there are many expectations within the party regarding Enrique Pena Nieto.
He rejects criticism from opponents who blame the new president for lack of charisma.
He is a whole man, very committed, with an excellent vision of the country.
He is an excellent statesman and, above all, he knows how to listen.
However, this is not always the image that the people have of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be more glaring.
Hidden under highway highways, it is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City.
And the problems in the municipality are also concrete and urban.
Earlier this year, the military was called to the rescue to fight drug gangs in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is particularly severe.
In a disaster zone, the bodies of dozens of women murdered in the last two years have been found on the landfill.
More than 1,000 women were killed in the state of Mexico while Mr. Pena Nieto was governor, a rate far higher than in the very violent city of Ciudad Juarez - a place infamous for the number of innocent women who were killed there.
Detractors of Mr. Pena Nieto, say that at best, he failed to stem the problem of murders perpetrated against women when he was in office.
At worst, they accuse his administration of refusing to face reality.
In a concrete house, typical of this dilapidated neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles to hold back her tears when she shows me photos of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
The official version mentions a suicide committed by Mariana in 2010.
However, her family thinks she was killed by her partner.
“When I arrived at her house, it seemed to me that her body had been washed,” says Señora Buendia.
Signs indicated that she had been beaten, and the cadaveric stiffness had already begun.
As her mother tells the story, a picture of Mariana dresses the wall, next to a cross with the word: Justice.
However, this is exactly what the family was refused.
The authorities treated me as if I were an old gossip, a troublemaker, a whiner.
They want us to accept what they're saying and shut up.
"But it's not normal that there are so many irregularities and omissions," she said.
When President Pena Nieto receives his scarf on Saturday, it will be accompanied by a heavy responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by crime in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has promised to make it his priority during his term.
“I hope he will be as good as he was as president when he was governor,” Olvera told Valle del Bravo, a member of Congress.
However, this is exactly what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, prosecutors said.
Prosecutors are trying to counter claims of mistreatment allegedly made by Bradley Manning during his detention.
The trial concerns Manning’s detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to close the case on the grounds that Manning's abduction took place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to show on Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of causing the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. military history -- missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claims he suffered during his military detention.
During a cross-examination with Manning during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney Maj. Ashden Fein stated that recordings of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not reveal any complaints about his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed an application requiring that Manning be dismissed on the grounds that the abduction took place under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- came a day after Manning testified to his desire to commit suicide during his detention.
The military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while serving in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At Friday’s hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that the officers had filled out after their meeting with Manning, during his detention in the Quantico military prison, where he was subjected to maximum solitary confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment his guards gave him was "excellent" and that the treatment he had received inside the prison was overall "very professional."
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning responded that he had orally expressed concerns about certain issues and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would address them, but they did not record the issues raised.
“They wrote ‘no problem’ (after addressing concerns), and yet that didn’t mean I didn’t raise any problems,” Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment in a January 2011 interview with the special commission that met to discuss suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to have his restrictive status changed to indicate a “risk of injury.”
The military said they had assigned him that restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was doing well, and I wanted to be removed from that status ... so that I could have a better quality of life from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine Corps base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he considered committing suicide while in Kuwait and fainted once because of the heat.
He added that not being kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage,” Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had were a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
He tried to stay on the move, because sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning also said that when he tried to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards could not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so they could see his face.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning’s treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked for a night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other detainees one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge’s questions on Friday, Manning said he had deduced from his guard’s order that he should drop his cover that might have hidden his nudity, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, as he allegedly tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic in his briefs or flip flops to injure himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account the experiences he had during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence if he is convicted in a court martial, a trial that is expected to be held early next year.
The defense said Manning is considering pleading guilty to the least serious offenses and fighting for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors arguing that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning has been detained in accordance with the rules governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include the theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information related to national defense.
If all charges are retained, he faces life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis
He says many have been forced to leave Mexico because of lack of opportunities.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left; they remind Mexicans of difficult times, he said.
Navarrette says the Mexican-Americans find themselves caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, arriving in the lobby, in front of the customs and immigration services, I felt lost.
Signs indicated two routes: one for the "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for the "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood still for several seconds, not knowing which way to go.
I grew up in central California, where I've been called the "Mexican" all my life.
It’s an ethnic qualifier, just like the one my friends in Boston use when they call themselves “Irish,” or my friends in New York when they call themselves “Italian.”
Then I became a Mexican-American.
But here it was Mexico.
And in the land where my grandfather was born, there is no need for a special qualification or a hyphen.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, well enough to handle an interview in either language.
But I don't have the vocabulary of an Aboriginal, and I can't lose my American accent.
So I took my American passport and headed to the "Foreigners" queue.
I thought about that moment of the week when the new Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited President Obama in the White House.
Generally, when the leaders of these two countries meet, their favorite themes are immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto also wanted to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one of the reasons Mexicans stay in Mexico rather than risk it in the United States.
He wants to ally with the United States and Canada, and create a Trade Union on the model of the European Union, but in North America.
And Pena Nieto pledges to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not provide more details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and bitter.
Most Americans probably never thought about the fact that in 1848, the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to give up half of their territory in writing at the point of the rifle.
But for Mexicans, who think in terms of centuries, not minutes, memories are everywhere.
Therefore, as soon as a U.S. official makes any criticism of Mexico, you begin to hear -- in the Mexican press, and among the elites -- complaints about how the Americans are undermining their neighbor's sovereignty.
And Montezuma's children are looking for the fight.
And yet, for Mexico, the most difficult relationship is the one that the country has with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Do you want to talk about bitterness?
There are a lot of them.
Mexico has its winners and its losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities and others for whom the country does not.
The only reason that explains the large number of Mexican ancestors in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, is that at some point, in our family tree, a person, perhaps a relative or grandparent, found no opportunity in Mexico and had to go to the North.
And most often, this person was a typical profile -- dark skin, poorly educated, from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendants, and we are loyal to them.
Not Mexico.
And even if we are currently living the American dream, going to good schools and having good situations, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream that we are living, and not that of the Mexicans.
Our identity is sometimes disturbed, but our loyalty is obvious.
We grant it to the United States.
Moreover, we know that a part of the Mexican elite among the ruling class does not like us.
The feeling is reciprocal.
We remind them of a humiliating defeat and they roast us as if we were inferior and not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
For them, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families had not failed when they lived in Mexico, they would never have left.
And we would not find ourselves stuck on the right side of the fence, living comfortably in the United States, but as lost souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there is friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans, because Mexicans are more firmly claiming their identity and Mexican-Americans are upset about it.
Although she is a U.S. citizen, she feels like she is part of two countries.
Moreover, many Mexican-Americans I know do not feel that they are part of one country or the other.
We love the music of the Mexican band, Los Tigres del Norte, but also that of Bruce Springsteen.
We have the best of both worlds, but we are not rooted in either.
In Mexico, we are considered Americans.
And in the United States, we are considered Mexicans.
And now, to complicate the relationship a little more, as I learned during my stay, some Mexican leaders and part of the intelligentsia want to get closer to the Diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as makeshift ambassadors for Mexico, representing its interests in the United States.
We will have to explain to our American compatriots that Mexico is a great country to visit and put pressure on political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course.
That's not going to happen.
There's too much bitterness.
And, considering the pervasive pay inequalities, corruption and drug-related violence, many of us are not convinced that this is a fantastic country.
You're gonna have to do it alone, amigos.
That's normal.
While some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, they must therefore accept that some Mexican-Americans still want them the way their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old disputes, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas is still a failure for peace.
Will there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed seems to indicate that such a hope is in vain.
While the same futile arguments persist for who started, dozens of buildings have been reduced to dust; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; and, for the first time, rockets fired from Gaza landed near Tel Aviv, the metropolis of Israel, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But while Israelis and Palestinians seem stuck in their old conflict, all around them, the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring shattered everything, and whether we like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis are caught up in this regional upheaval.
Perhaps their struggle will intensify a little more.
Yet, there is every reason to think that it could help them get out of this deadly impasse.
A war that makes no losers and no winners
At first glance, it seems difficult to be optimistic.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 is maintained, this week’s fighting has strengthened supporters of the force on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will boast of forcing Israelis to give up, even though Gaza has been beaten.
Having killed some of its leaders and pushed back the 1.7 million inhabitants of Gaza into one of the most miserable and overpopulated corners of the planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently in the hands of its rivals Fatah, the other more moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders might say that time is their ally.
The influence of Islamists in the Arab world is growing stronger, and Hamas has made rich and powerful friends.
Turkey, a burgeoning regional power, once Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken up the cause of Hamas; just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic states in the Gulf.
Hamas members rejoice and say that the Islamist crescent is bent around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, where Hezbollah militia exerts its dominance, to Syria, where Islamist-leaning rebels can overthrow Bashar El Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And most importantly, on Israel’s southern flank, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under the presidency of Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and central of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time to devote to Hamas.
On the other hand, the Muslim Brotherhood is a cousin of Hamas, and their leaders are more likely to rely on public opinion.
In future diplomacy, Hamas can emerge as a major player that can no longer be excluded even by Israel and America.
Meanwhile, Israel’s hardliners will draw the opposite conclusions.
In military terms, Hamas has been put back into a box.
The missile interception system dubbed Iron Dome has proven its effectiveness and many Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
Israelis will be able to sleep on both ears - for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, America renews its unwavering support; and many European countries have blamed Hamas for being behind the latest wave of violence.
Above all, Israel prospered, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who totally ignored the peace process.
Although Gaza rocket fire has killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has been spared from suicide bombings, notably thanks to the separation barrier that encroaches on the West Bank, the main piece of what could be a Palestinian state, and which protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite their illegality under international law.
Netanyahu, whose Likud party has merged with an even more bellicose party, that of leader Avigdor Lieberman ahead of the January 22 election, has the nice part.
Why pamper these damn Palestinians by giving them a state?
If they were to run the West Bank, would they not launch rockets, as their compatriots did in Gaza?
It is best to keep them behind that wall and hit them as soon as they come out of the head.
Perhaps the hardliners will win; but the Arab Spring may be a game changer.
Even if the Islamists who seize power in Egypt and elsewhere have little appreciation for Israel, their priority will be to address problems in their own countries.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the local superpower will not help the new Arab governments fix their economies.
Mr. Morsi worked with Barack Obama to get a ceasefire that bodes well -- and could mark the beginning of something.
Israelis should also think about the future.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination could create a powder keg that is doomed to explode one day in Israeli-occupied territories — much like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression already weakens democracy in the Jewish state, and demographics exacerbate this problem as the Arab population grows.
The bloody missions to Gaza every two or three years to ring the bell of Hamas will come at a diplomatic price.
Both sides need to be pushed by those from the outside.
The answer remains the one advocated by the reasonable people on either side, and by most of the outside world and by this newspaper: two states, with a transfer of territory by Israel in exchange for security.
One hope, small and short-term, is that the ceasefire will give outsiders an opportunity to defend this cause.
Egypt, which must now work to end the flow of arms to Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is better placed than ever to persuade Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state in accordance with the 1967 borders with exchanges of land and a shared Jerusalem.
Arabs from outside countries should also put pressure on Hamas and Fatah to unite.
This would contribute much more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the forthcoming proposal of a pseudo-state at the United Nations.
Mr. Obama also has every interest in Israel agreeing to negotiate.
During his first term, he did not present his own peace plan.
Back in the White House, he seems equally reluctant to establish one.
It's a very narrow vision.
The stability of the Middle East is a vital issue for America.
This requires a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Laws for neutral cigarette packs come into force in Australia
Warnings and photos of diseased organs cover the dark green packages that are all identical, regardless of the brand
This law came into force in Australia is a world first, the logos and colors have been replaced by a dark olive green and horrible pictures of sick organs and depictions of children and babies whose diseases were caused by their parents' smoking.
Apart from the different photos and health warnings, the only difference between the packages, since this Saturday, is the brand name, printed in small print on all the packages.
This is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
The Australian federal government said the goal was to deter young people from smoking by removing any glamorous depiction.
Studies have shown that if people have not started smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that they will never start.
"Even when they are very young, children understand the message conveyed by tobacco manufacturers through their brand image," said federal health minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that revealed for example that children associated the crown of a logo with a princess.
Although Australia has the lowest smoking rate in the world and these changes have little impact on the profits of multinationals, other countries are considering a similar approach.
The tobacco industry has lobbied against this law.
Tobacco makers said it would revive black market trade, which will give easier access to cheaper cigarettes.
“There will be harmful consequences from this legislation,” said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
The counterfeiters of China and Indonesia will sell far more counterfeit cigarettes on the streets of Australia.
Others said that this law had boosted their activity.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned business, said demand for cigarette cases, including silicone cases to hide hideous packaging, had risen sharply two months ago since British American Tobacco, Britain’s Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco challenged the law and lost in Australia’s high court.
