"I'm going to work another two years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Struggling with life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but, instead, he does the job of a mule.
It shares an unhealthy wooden stall with other bearers, rises every day at two o'clock in the morning as sulfur does not cease to gush at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater by illuminating himself with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable benefits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur extraction to save costs and does not provide any equipment to carriers who work on their own and are paid by weight.
In addition, they also do not receive a sub of the 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) of surcharge per camera, in addition to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros), which the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This work is done for animals, not humans,” protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old body carrier who has been working at Kawah Ijen for 30 years since he left college.
Capable of carrying up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can", because he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18 years.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke that come out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases... to which are obviously added their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and shoulders.
By balancing the basket on his back, 53-year-old Unainik can only carry 50 kilos.
Each day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away by a goat trail overgrown with weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life," Unainik said, opening his mouth, revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of his five children, aged 30, also works as a sulphur carrier.
Time passes, but the misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult professions in the world: that of the human mules of the Kawah ljen volcano.
Singapore looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans lay the blame for this childlessness on the career, stress and cost of access to property.
“Singapore’s population needs to grow.”
I am a husband and a patriot, you are my wife and a patriot, let us fulfill our civic duty and give life!
It may seem implausible that these lyrics come from an advertisement for mint pellets, but despite this, or perhaps thanks to this, the video spread like wildfire on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The lyrics come from a rap group that uses local references like "Let's put a polichinelle in the drawer" to mock Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency behind the video, hopes to draw attention to the problem in a fun way with this ad.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, said he wanted to use the power of music to get people to fulfill “their national duty.”
It is intended for the Internet only, so we were able to make it fun and entertaining.
This is the main problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in the field of birth, so we felt it was a theme that we needed to address.
We knew that the government had tried several things like throwing pheromone perfumes or organizing speed-dating parties.
Many of these ideas were creative, but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we thought to ourselves, what could be more creative to solve this problem than to turn it into a rap song?
1.2 Children
The government of Singapore does not take it so lightly.
He spends $1,300 a year on politics to encourage his citizens to have more children.
A government measure in favor of marriages and fathers grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
The birth rate of Singapore, in accordance with its national population distribution, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2, considered the renewal rate, was in 1976.
Why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policy at the National Population Division, said it was due to “better education” and “a wider choice of career opportunities.”
“This has given people a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and family formation,” she says.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the increase in the number of singles and delayed marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counter population decline has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that abound in barely disguised xenophobia against new immigrants, especially Chinese who are accused of pulling wages down and failing to integrate.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore’s ruling party experienced its worst election results since independence last year.
Since the elections, they have tried to correct the problem with the introduction of higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While falling birth rates have known effects on a country’s economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore’s example also has unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, this has started to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and their sale is very successful.
However, the authorities are concerned that they can promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers wishing to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, general manager of real estate company EL Developers, says its “shoe boxes” sell much faster than larger homes.
They are more popular, in the sense that these dwellings are built much faster than larger ones.
For this reason, it is much more profitable for our treasury.
However, he acknowledged that the new standards gave clearer instructions to developers, who had previously been put a stick in the wheels if they wanted to offer too many small dwellings in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
If so that these new regulations can be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by talking with Singaporeans who work in the central financial district, it would seem that they are not going to have much effect.
“People are very stressed, homes are expensive, just like education, that’s why people put it off,” says one young executive.
Other people can have children.
"But for me, it's important to be able to have my money and my time," another 20-year-old tells us.
Men and women mention their careers, stress and the cost of access to property and education as the reasons preventing them from having children.
So while the government is trying to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans themselves have the final say.
What is private offline is private online
Confidentiality
According to the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, this is the quality of the private domain or "the domain of privacy that we can protect from any intrusion".
What is the private domain for children under 16?
How to apply this definition in daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers to which he exposes himself by broadcasting events on the Internet that he would certainly not share offline?
The newspaper elPeriódico interviewed five young boys, aged between 10 and 15, frequent users of the web.
In four of the cases, they associated the term “something very personal” on a personal level and “password and username” when they applied it to social networks.
“I’m not going to reveal my most personal secrets in a post,” says Jorge, 10, when he tries to explain the meaning of the term private on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had an account for two years.
