On FB, I post nice images or games.
I also talk with my friends.
“I’m not going to share one of my pictures or someone who would be a fool,” he said.
The boy admits that it is wrong to post obscene photos, naked people, crimes or write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge assures that he knows his 35 friends on FB as well as his nine followers on Twitter.
The majority are family.
Her mother is one of them, she knows the password of one of the accounts.
I opened a Twitter account to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if they answer me, I just post them," he adds.
“Social media is fun, I can talk to distant relatives or friends quickly,” he says.
He says he would never accept the request of an unknown person.
Nor will he trust anyone who would recommend him a stranger.
The case of Joseph, 14, is different.
The teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, on the latter he admits not knowing 20 of the people registered on his friends list.
“I’m not worried because we have something in common, like music,” he says.
According to the boy, no one made any advances or asked for his address or phone number.
“If they put pressure on me or demanded it, I would simply remove them from my account,” he said.
José subscribed to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The experiences we know today as cyberbullying are not unfamiliar to the young boy.
A friend of mine was hacked into a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
“He never knew who it was,” he said.
The victim, according to José, did not close his account.
"He just passed it on to a private profile."
He then explains to us a series of manipulations to configure his account in a safe way.
Unlike Jorge, this young man would post photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would if I was angry or upset.
“Even though I know it’s cyberbullying,” he says.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and graduate in Education and Learning, believes that, to guide children and adolescents, one must understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet has emerged as a way to search for information but, with the appearance of these sites, the rules of the game have changed," she said.
Porras points out that academic Marc Prensky, who holds a master's degree in pedagogy from Yale University and author of the book "Natives and Digital Immigrants", uses these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital natives are they, children and young people who are born with technology.
“We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them there, while we are learning ourselves,” she says.
He adds that the theme is complex, "because we ask them to have a definite criterion on what should or should not be disclosed, published or said at an age when they do not have the maturity necessary to do so."
"We also ask them to be selective when what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," she added.
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach children and adolescents about privacy is to use questions that make them think.
“Their saying not to do it is useless,” she says.
Then Porras lists a few examples: there are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like them to post a picture of you like that of a friend you posted?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you identify holiday photos, do you ask other people for permission to identify them?
And also, does everyone need to know what you do at every moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they need to act online as they do offline.
These are the same rules.
“Outside of the Internet, everyone must act with respect, morality and other principles, it must be the same on social media,” she said.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, primary school teacher and education adviser, said it was essential for parents to read the terms of use of social networks conscientiously.
By understanding each of the terms, they will have a solid foundation to discuss with their children the implications of opening an account on the Internet.
“For example, age and what it is allowed to share or publish,” he says.
According to Guardia, it is essential to remind children not to talk to strangers.
The UNASUR summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 mandataries present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of UNASUR Heads of State and Government, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the presidency initially reported that it would be disclosed after the end of the summit, then said it would be published at any time on the Peruvian government's website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by Peruvian President Ollante Humala in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been constantly restricted.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, audio restricted" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information circulating among the journalists was given by the press attachés of some of the UNASUR governments attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document leaked during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some unease among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more important information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency sent an email to the media with the summit’s “final declaration,” but it was President Humala’s speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South America-Arab Countries (ASPA) Summit and, on that occasion, although it had been urged to do so by the press, it had also not issued the declaration also known as the Lima Declaration, as had previously been announced.
On the official website of ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to put in place safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the obtaining of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court that settles a border difference between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ’s decision to hear the pleas of both sides in the Lima trial against Santiago that begins Monday in The Hague.
“We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we have today before this international court,” Humala said, speaking alongside his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country respectful of international law, the peaceful resolution of international controversies, treaties and tribunals,” Piñera said, shaking hands with President Humala alongside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia this week denounced the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international tribunal, after a decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua which it considered to be seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from UNASUR since 2011 after the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been set between the South American countries for a total of $ 17 million of investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and against international organized crime, actions for better accessibility to medicines, access to cheap Internet throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to envision a better future for our populations," concluded President Humala.
“We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” the Peruvian president said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on the transverse axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador although he did not give further details.
Similarly, the outcome document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process of this country will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," he said.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and with good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through an ICJ judgment requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We will review all these avenues, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask to have a discussion with this country," he said.
"I hope I can tell President Ortega that we will deal with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to attend the seizure of power of the country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, as part of the summit, the bloc's defence ministers will meet in advance to endorse the 2013 Plan of Action, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the presidency pro tempore of the regional bloc.
“South America needs to learn from Europe how to integrate citizenship,” says Rafael Correa.
Ecuador's President Rafael Correa said today that the creation of a common citizenship was an objective for which "South America, in this case, should take the example of Europe".
President Correa, who participated in the 6th summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), located in Lima, told state television, TV Perú, that Europeans "had killed each other during the Second World War" and other conflicts, "but that they were now almost a homeland".
