We do not negotiate with human rights, we do not use that word in this case, but there have been ongoing discussions.
“The solution to this problem lies in the hands of Britain, Sweden and the European judicial authorities because Assange’s lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, has launched a whole series of proceedings in different European instances,” he said.
And he thinks that “if Britain granted the safe haul as early as tomorrow, it would end.”
And if Sweden, as its legislation allows, and as it has already done in other cases, were to question Mr. Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy in London, or were to question him via Skype tomorrow, the problem would also be solved.
Correa took the opportunity to reaffirm himself as a defender of press freedom and said that what he did not tolerate was "mediocrity, bad faith and lies that harm freedom of expression".
“The greatest enemies of press freedom are not malevolent or perverse politicians but bad journalists on the payroll of greed, blackmail and extortion,” he said.
From this point of view, he welcomed the fact that this is not the kind of journalists "neither the bankers nor the hegemonic and bourgeois countries that dominate in Ecuador" and, rather than highlighting his re-election, "he would deepen the revolution to continue the path and chart the right path".
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto on Paraguay within Unasur at least until the next elections, arguing that the organization "should be firm and not tolerate opportunism and disguised coup attempts," because in reality, "it destroyed the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy."
Moreover, the Ecuadorian president considers as "perfectly relevant" the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries through the judgment of the International Court of The Hague, which will strengthen Nicaragua's maritime sovereignty.
At the moment, this judgment is not respected.
This is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to move forward together.
We have to solve them as a whole to overcome them and move forward.
At the same time, he said he was confident in the proper resolution of the maritime border dispute between Peru and Chile in the same court and affirmed that it is "beneficial for Latin America to refer to international bodies if both countries agree to accept a judgment as firm as it may be".
Referring to the possibility of his presentation as a candidate in the upcoming presidential elections in Ecuador, with a view to running for a third consecutive term, he noted that he sees this possibility "with a lot of optimism and joy, although it is sometimes quite difficult".
Correa assured that if he lost the February 2013 primaries, he would withdraw from public life.
On a personal level, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unjust as those in Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be solved through political power.
"My political movement believed that it was me who guaranteed this eventual victory but we must accept this responsibility," he said.
If I win, it would be my last presidential term and I will then withdraw from political life.
If we ever lose, I will too.
"It's my decision," he said.
Correa also referred to the new medical treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez in Cuba.
I just spoke with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he told me that routine medical treatment was already planned and that he was waiting for the end of the campaign to return to Cuba.
"This does not mean a relapse of President Chavez's health," he said.
The Ecuadorian head of state participated today in Lima at the 6th Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) which ended with a call for better regional integration in order to support progress, equality and security.
AIDS-related deaths today are due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 years old when the test result was confirmed: HIV-positive.
"It was as if the sky had fallen on my head," he said, referring to the announcement, which the doctor had tried to make "less painful" in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to inquire about him and his relentlessness was such that he just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is, without a doubt, one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), in which he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something hard to imagine in the early 90s, where there were many doubts, few treatment choices and more stigmas.
Then, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was speechless."
In those days, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their disease, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "depleted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first reported cases, "the great victory is today that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the general population is exactly the same," said the head of the HIV unit of the HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva and he takes as a reference that this information was validated in April of this year.
Infectiologist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a deadly disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depends on the level of immune system involvement patients had at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those with CD rates up to 50 years for those who do not use drugs: up to a CD rate of 50 for those with a CD rate of up to 30 years for those who do not use drugs.
To put it simply, this means that for someone who would receive an HIV-positive diagnosis at age 25, "as long as he remains under control, he will be able to live without problems up to 75 years," the scientist explained.
In order to put this progress in context, it is necessary to know that the life expectancy of Mexicans is now 76 years on average.
While it is true that mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS increased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), but it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60% of the patients identified on the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths as of May this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
So why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem comes from access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over the last 12 years at least, we have never been short of drugs, the problem is that patients reach very advanced stages because they do not know that they are infected, or else they learn it in advanced stages of the disease.
“Nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what it takes to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, for this, we must offer massive screening tests to all people who ask for it.”
Specialists and members of the Jalisco State Council for AIDS Prevention (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as do the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to do his screening test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and that, despite his young age, he was already a carrier of AIDS and suffered from carcinoma.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't want to know.
“If I’m going to die, it’s better that I have fun three times a week,” they say, not my case.
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medications.
To date, his parents only know that he has cancer.
I have a normal life, just like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active but co-responsible sex life, I pay attention to myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the march of World AIDS Day.
If they do the test, if they have taken risks, the sooner they will know if they are HIV-positive and the better, and if they already have the diagnosis, they need to know that you can live like everyone else, being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the battle against AIDS in this year 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programs and the ordinary citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has embraced the cause of HIV.
And the biggest one is prevention.
In all the places dedicated to this, "we have actually increased the distribution of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are given packets of one hundred, it is very good, but it results, that even today, some do not have access to condoms," he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
The question: "What are you going to do with it?", posed with sarcasm and value judgments by social workers, counsellors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teenagers do not want to hear, says the journalist.
He proposes to redirect this inefficient distribution; that condoms not only be sold at counters, but that they be found in distributors in public toilets and in places frequented by young people.
It is not about encouraging promiscuity.
Nor is it about paying for the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González responded when asked if there would be a distribution of condoms within his administration.
“This is not how sexuality works, the best thing is to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active,” he said.
Numbers in Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 of AIDS and 1,317 of HIV).
The state is the 4th state in the country in the number of new and cumulative cases of AIDS and 13th in the number of HIV patients.
92% of infections occur through sexual contact, 6% through blood and 2% through perinatal contact.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV, since for each recorded case, there are 4 or 5 people who are unaware of it.
A ruling upheld by a U.S. court ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group’s debt through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico, setting a damaging precedent for all domestic companies with ramifications in the neighboring country and having solvency problems.
Thus, it seems that the procedures for the survival of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the country with the starry flag, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the judgement handed down on June 15 by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican companies defenseless in the face of the possibility of embargoing their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico’s top glassmaker to sue the U.S. Supreme Court based on three inconsistencies.
First, while the judge of the case notes that creditors must register under the U.S. Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, sitting in New Orleans, states that the main proceeding is the commercial bankruptcy formalized in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Commercial Law had been created for this purpose by taking the American Law Institute as its arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment establishes that without the intercompany vote, recognised in the critical mass of commercial bankruptcy, the debts incurred by Vitro's subsidiaries towards the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
In fact, the case of Vitro is not the first to use this plan.
There are half a dozen examples here, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcies.
Moreover, what is certain is that, since the votes of the subsidiaries remained, in any case the creditors of Vitro who fought against this in the courts of the United States, i.e. vulture funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained the majority.
The vote would have been 45 to 37.
