Hector "Hetin" Reyes "Basketball is my whole life"
The basketball globetrotter "Hetin" Reyes spent more than 60 years of his life in connection with the field and, thanks to him, traveled the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as much knowledge of the history of local basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason for this is that before a brain hemorrhage condemned him to wheelchair use in 2008, Reyes had been immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower-league player, basketball national team player, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as president of the fed.
"I have worn several hats in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was president of the BSN, director general of the national team and president of the federation during the 90s," Reyes recalled during a Primera Hora visit to his home in Bayamón, where he has resided with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
“Basketball is my whole life.”
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes this claim.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that recall his extraordinary itinerary, bear witness to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he loves most are those that remind him of his time as a player on the Vaqueros team in the mid-1950s until 1982, after spending 15 years as a co-manager or manager of the team.
“These were my best years, the ones that I enjoyed the most because I had the chance to participate in eight Vaqueros championships since 1967, whether as a manager, co-manager or manager.
This is a lot of years of satisfaction, including the five championships played from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired at the championship in 1981, the year that Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead of the team," Reyes said.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been a leader here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), he said to me, "I have a strong player for you, he's two meters tall.
Do you want it?"
That's how to start Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and was one of the best shooters.
I remember he said that if Mincy allowed Bayamon to win one championship, Gausse would help us try to win another.
He was delighted with the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the great manitou of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of his and Mincy's positions in the national team.
I remember when we first won it in the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we got 4th and where we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge hadn’t let us play the last game,” Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, just like the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won gold and beat the U.S. team, which was pretty similar to the one that won bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the World Cup of 90 because of a knee problem.
A team that may not be the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and great joy in the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hurruitiner replacing the players suspended by the imbroglio of the Pan American Games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold against all odds.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, it is Piculín Ortiz.
His statistics on international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at this level like Piculín.
And this without taking into account his trajectory in the different leagues for which he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very hard to say.
We had a good team made up of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I really like the work that Leo Arill does.
For you, what is your greatest achievement within the federation?
To have been part of the most glorious era of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s, the BSN had up to 17 teams in a season.
What do you have left to do?
There are things that I would have liked to put in place, such as the regionalization of minor categories.
For example, the Ponce boys play only in their zone and only face teams from other corners of the island in the national playoffs.
Today, young people travel and play too much when this is not necessarily necessary.
I have at least seen the advantage of mandatory certifications and courses for leaders, field staff and referees.
It makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
In general, I listen to music, watch clips from my time on YouTube, take advantage of my grandchildren, and occasionally attend basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became known worldwide for the leading role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he played an unscrupulous, fearsome and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas," died Friday night of complications from cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., the production house of "Dallas."
“Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, playing the ironic role he loved most,” the family said.
Larry’s family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and the sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, his press secretary Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he was living life to the full," Gray said in a statement.
Doctors diagnosed Larry Hagman with liver cirrhosis in 1992, and he admitted to drinking heavily for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant liver tumor and had undergone a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas," Hagman had made a name for himself on television in the role of an ordinary guy on the NBC series "Jinny of My Dreams" from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered an enticing genius, played by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971–72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film roles include critically acclaimed roles in "The Band", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was through his masterful portrayal of the delightfully detestable J.R. that Larry Hagman achieved his greatest success.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and their relatives aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan “Who Killed J.R.?”, invented to fuel suspense around an emotionally charged episode in which Hagman’s character is nearly murdered, has generated worldwide speculation and millions of dollars played in bets.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached an audience record at that time.
When the answer was revealed in an episode in November 1980, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screens and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who had shot him.
J.R. had made her pregnant and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but other people also had reasons to assault her.
Hagman played Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who was trying to get his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) interned.
"I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R," Hagman said in 1988.
We should write, "Here lies the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only part he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, recalled this Friday Hagman as a man "immense, both on the small screen and in life."
It’s unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of all of us, who’ve had the chance to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were aired a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
Recording for five episodes has already been completed for the second season and a sixth is underway, the channel said.
So far, neither Warner nor TNT has said how Hagman’s death will be included in the series.
Originally from Fort Worth, Texas, he is the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who rose to fame with classic works such as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Mary Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth to him in 1931 when she was married to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He made his first steps on stage in New York theaters in the early 1950s and then served in the Air Force from 1952 to 1956 in England.
It was there that he met and married the young Swedish interior designer Maj Axelsson.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for many years in the California city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he titled his memoirs "Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life" (in French: Hello Darlin': Les mémoires impitoyables de J.R)
“I haven’t written anything in this book that could hurt anyone or affect them in any way,” he told reporters at the time.
After his liver transplant, he became an active organ donation activist and worked as a volunteer in a hospital to assist concerned patients.
"I advise them, I give them confidence, I come with them when they come to have surgery and then," he says in 1996.
I’m trying to offer them some comfort, like, “Don’t be afraid, it won’t be easy for a little while, but it’s going to be fine.”
He has also been an anti-tobacco activist and has participated in several campaigns.
A course on the "End of the World" has just begun
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when Charmed Religion Professor Stuart decided to give a lesson on the end of the world, he knew that he was throwing an irresistible hook: the end of the "great tally" of the Mayan calendar, on December 21, which many people refer to as proof of the imminent end of the world.
But Professor Charmed had no idea what awaited him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a fiscal chasm that some have dubbed “the Armageddon of debt” and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where end-time Christian theorists thought the apocalypse would unfold.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," Charmed told his students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If you look at what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and tell it, it was a very good time.
And it must be remembered that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he's not the only teacher to give classes on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
In Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker teaches the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We’re analyzing this because these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human behavior.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real-life examples.
“I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply titled “The End of the World.”
“We’re adding ‘2012’ to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world doesn’t disappear,” Restall said.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The classes proved to be quite popular.
“It was complete in two hours,” Restall said of his 35-student high-level course.
We received emails several weeks before the start of the semester from people asking if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves,” says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student of religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, Rutgers-Camden University.
For fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, claims to have watched all the apocalyptic movies.
“I had never heard of a course that taught this subject,” he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students interviewed, let alone a professor, told us they believed in the end-of-the-world date of December 21.
“Our first project was about Mayan prophecy, and somehow we discredited it,” says Julie Zegle, a 21-year-old senior at Temple, West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world, it’s just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I concede that there is an apocalypse-related anxiety in Western culture, dating back several centuries, that causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has led to a rise in this speculation.
“In other places around the globe, people don’t think about that,” he says.
This is mostly the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who teaches in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew there were classes here on "the end of the world."
"The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world," he replied, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall notes that over the years there has been talk of the many supposed dates of the Last Judgment, and he states that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 marks the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Many told us that they thought they were going to “end-of-the-world” parties.
“Sometimes I call friends and we laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
